description: From Latin generātus, perfect passive participle of generō (“beget, procreate, produce”), from genus (“a kind, race, family”); see genus.

verbs.description: generate (third-person singular simple present generates, present participle generating, simple past and past participle generated)

entries.meaning: (transitive) To bring into being; give rise to.
(transitive) To produce as a result of a chemical or physical process.
examples: Adding concentrated sulphuric acid to water generates heat.

entries.meaning: (transitive, mathematics) To form a figure from a curve or solid.
examples: Rotating a circle generates a sphere.

entries.meaning: (intransitive) To appear or occur; be generated.
examples: Mrs. Fennel, seeing the steam begin to generate on the countenances of her guests, crossed over and touched the fiddler's elbow and put her hand on the serpent's mouth.
